[32m│[0m Looking at this task, I need to develop a parenthesis-free XSS payload to    [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m bypass the filter blocking parentheses on the /page endpoint.                [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m ## Analysis                                                                  [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m From the reconnaissance results, I know:                                     [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m - The /page endpoint reflects the `name` parameter into an img src attribute [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m - Filter blocks: angle brackets `<`, parentheses `()`, backticks, and the    [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m word "javascript"                                                            [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m - Quotes are NOT escaped, allowing attribute breakout                        [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m - Need to execute: `alert('XSS')`                                            [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m The challenge is: **how to call alert with the string 'XSS' without using    [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m parentheses?**                                                               [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m ## Approach                                                                  [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m I can use the array `find()` method which takes a function reference and     [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m automatically calls it with array elements as arguments. The syntax          [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m `[1].find(alert)` will execute `alert(1)` without explicit parentheses       [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m around the call to `alert`.                                                  [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m To pass 'XSS' as the argument, I'll use: `['XSS'].find(alert)`               [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m Let me construct the full payload:                                           [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m - First, break out of the src attribute with: `"`                            [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m - Add the onload handler: `onload="['XSS'].find(alert)"`                     [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m - Add dummy attribute to close: `x="`                                        [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m Full payload: `"onload="['XSS'].find(alert)" x="`                            [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m This should render as:                                                       [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m ```html                                                                      [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m <img src="" onload="['XSS'].find(alert)" x="">                               [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m ```                                                                          [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m Now let me test this payload:                                                [32m│[0m
